<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><xmi:XMI xmlns:type3="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/frequency/tfidf/type.ecore" xmlns:cas="http:///uima/cas.ecore" xmlns:type4="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/metadata/type.ecore" xmlns:dependency="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type/dependency.ecore" xmlns:type8="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type.ecore" xmlns:type9="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/type.ecore" xmlns:type5="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/ner/type.ecore" xmlns:type6="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/segmentation/type.ecore" xmlns:tcas="http:///uima/tcas.ecore" xmlns:pathos="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/argumentation/types/pathos.ecore" xmlns:tweet="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/lexmorph/type/pos/tweet.ecore" xmlns:chunk="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type/chunk.ecore" xmlns:type7="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/semantics/type.ecore" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:type2="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/coref/type.ecore" xmlns:toulmin="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/argumentation/types/toulmin.ecore" xmlns:morph="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/lexmorph/type/morph.ecore" xmlns:types="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/argumentation/types.ecore" xmlns:constituent="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/syntax/type/constituent.ecore" xmlns:type="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/anomaly/type.ecore" xmlns:pos="http:///de/tudarmstadt/ukp/dkpro/core/api/lexmorph/type/pos.ecore" xmi:version="2.0"><cas:NULL xmi:id="0"/><cas:Sofa xmi:id="1" sofaNum="1" sofaID="_InitialView" mimeType="text" sofaString="I think it's not as big a deal to homeschool in earlier grades but it's often a disservice to older kids to do so in say middle or high school. Those years teach a lot of responsibility in regards to school. Going from class to class on time, gaining maturity to handle yourself in school and juggle multiple classes/teachers, learning how to &quot;learn from&quot; different teachers/styles, etc. Not to mention sports and activities and the community and social feeling of being in a school, that has nothing to do with your family or mom, and gaining indepedence. I suppose a lot of my &quot;pro-school&quot; arguments have to do more with those aspects than actual curriculum. And no I'm not a huge &quot;fan&quot; of homeschooled kids being homeschooled but then joining the local HS volleyball team. I get it, taxes for schools are paid by them too, so it's &quot;OK&quot; but you aren't really part of that &quot;school&quot;. I'm jaded - I had a cousin who was homeschooled most of her life, in and out of a few religious schools, but mostly at home. Suddenly it was &quot;OK&quot; to go to public school her senior year - so she could make use of their post secondary program and get free college credits. Working the system a bit there. Always irritated me. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1208" language="en" documentId="509" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="mamaKto2under2" date="09/05/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=13" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="509" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1208"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>